text=(:essential: yes:)%0a(:deadline: 2021-05-01:)%0a(:expansiondeadline: 2021-05-08:)%0a%0a!!Linguistic Discrimination in the Wild%0a(:if equal yes yes:)%0a('''essential category''')%0a(:if end:)%0a%0a----%0a%0aLinguistic discrimination can take many forms, but generally refers to discrimination based on how a person uses language; e.g., due to their accent (sometimes called accentism), morphosyntactic features of their dialect, lexical differences, or due to the fact that they use signed rather than spoken language.%0a%0a'''NOTE:'''  The examples cited in this category may be triggering to those who use the dialects and languages represented.  Please be mindful of this when you post.  If you are a user of a minoritized language or dialect, then please be aware that the examples on this page may be triggering.%0a%0aIn this wiki category you are asked to find examples of linguistic discrimination “in the wild”: in media, on the internet at large, in a class syllabus (but please, no instructor names), etc.  There are two parts to an article of this type:%0a* [+ Post a link to the example; if derogatory language is included, please make sure to include a click warning. +]%0a* [+ Using appropriate linguistic terminology, what is the example decrying as ungrammatical?  For example, if the criticism refers to the pronunciation of “first” as [fɪɹs] instead of [fɪɹst], then the criticism is about the application of the rule of final consonant deletion.+]%0a* [+ Determine which dialect the criticized variant belongs to. +]%0a%0a!!Expansions%0a%0aExpansions in this category could be additional discussion/commentary, the curation of additional examples, the comparison of the example with forms from other languages, etc.  Note that if you post articles in both this category and in [[Category.MorphosyntacticDiversity |Morphosyntactic Diversity]], you must make sure that you write about different grammatical constructions.%0a%0a%0a----
